&gt;The types of the Java programming language are divided into two categories: primitive types and reference types. The primitive types [...] are the boolean type and the numeric types. The numeric types are the integral types byte, short, int, long, and char, and the floating-point types float and double. The reference types [...] are class types, interface types, and array types. There is also a special null type. An object [...] is a dynamically created instance of a class type or a dynamically created array. The values of a reference type are references to objects. All objects, including arrays, support the methods of class Object [...].

